data <- read.csv("Hitters.csv")

Part 1

1.

data <- data %>% drop_na(Salary)

ggplot(data, aes(x = Salary)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Salary")

data$logSalary <- log(data$Salary)

ggplot(data, aes(x = logSalary)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of log(Salary)")

##The histogram is right skewed, meaning that most players have salaries on the lower end with some on the higher end. After log-transformation, the histogram shows characteristics of a normal distribution.

2.

ggplot(data, aes(x = Hits, y = logSalary, color = League)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of log(Salary) vs. Hits with Smoothed Lines")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

3.

model <- lm(logSalary ~ Hits * League, data = data)

##I would choose the seperate slope model because Hits and Log Salary are differentiated by League. The interaction term is significant.

4.

##American League = 0.011 100 = 1.1%; National league = (0.011 0.004) 100 = 0.7%

5.

plot(model)

set.seed(29101)

data_default <- read.csv("Default.csv")

11.

ggplot(data_default, aes(x = income)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Income for Population") +
  theme_minimal()

sd_income <- sd(data_default$income)

12.

By Central Limit Theorem, the distribution of the sample mean tends to be normal regardless of the original distribution of the variable

13.

sample_data_default <- sample_n(data_default, 100)

ggplot(sample_data_default, aes(x = income)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 15, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Income for Sample (n = 100)") +
  theme_minimal()

mean_income_sample <- mean(sample_data_default$income)
sd_income_sample <- sd(sample_data_default$income)
mean_income_sample
## [1] 35.73587
sd_income_sample
## [1] 12.57488
